    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The `IndexError: list index out of range` usually happens when you try to access an index that doesn't exist, often because your loop logic doesn't match the actual list length. For example, if you're using a `range()` function that goes one step too far, or if the list is being modified while iterating, you'll get this error.\n\nYou should fix your loop bounds by ensuring the range matches the list size exactly, or switch to iterating directly over the list items instead of using indices. This will prevent your code from trying to access a non-existent index at the end of the list.\n\nHere is a quick example of how to correct the logic:\n\n```python\n# Bad: Assuming the list is longer than it is\nfor i in range(len(files) + 1): \n    print(files[i])\n\n# Good: Iterating directly over the list\nfor file in files:\n    print(file)\n```\n\nIf you still encounter issues after fixing the loop, please share the specific code snippet so I can spot any hidden bugs.",
